>>69451654
Lots of trial and error, along with a decent amount of time to do/practice and refine.
I had some basic knowledge of stop-motion animation when getting into 3D but the workflow became clear after watching this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jt1ifwe5PYs
The key to achieving "smoothness" is to form an interpolation of motion with your keyframes. Start with a linear animation, then add keyframes in between the linear keyframes to express a sense of weight and liveliness to your animation.
It helps to take into account how movement at one part of the body influences the other (raising the arm brings the shoulder up with it, moving legs will swing the hips, body and torso sway, etc). Blender's Rigify and its inverse kinematics are also a lifesaver as the knees and elbows move on their own according to where the feet and hands are place, respectively.
Although I am busy at the moment, I've considered making a pool of resources and homemade tutorials to help explain and demonstrate all these kinds of things. Would anybody be interested in such a thing in the future?
